embeds.title: FPS and Game Speed Explained!
embeds.description:
Many games that are exclusively released on consoles run at 30 or 60FPS, for example Wind Waker HD and Mario Kart 8. The creators of these games made sure that it reaches that FPS (most of the time) on the Wii U. For simplicity, they also decide that all the gameplay, animations, physics etc. will run at that game speed of 30 or 60FPS, respectively.

But when you're emulating your PC will be faster or slower than the Wii U itself. When your PC runs slower then the Wii U, it won't be able to play those gameplay, animations, physics etc. at it's full speed, so the game speed will be slower.

Multiple games like Breath of the Wild have community-made graphic packs that change a lot of things in the game like gameplay, animations, physics etc. to run at a different (dynamic) FPS. However, not everything is changed to this new FPS so you will run into (small) issues!

@Deleted User Alright, sorry that I couldn't respond.

What you likely wanna do is create/add an ultrawide patch to the Graphics pack of this game that (I assume) exists, so that it scales with the resolution that you pick in the Graphics.

First, find your game's `Graphics` (it should include a rules.txt file directly inside it) folder from inside the `YourCemuFolder/graphicPacks/downloadedGraphicPacks folder`,  and move it up so that the `Graphics` folder is directly under the root of the `graphicPacks` folder BUT outside of the `downloadedGraphicPacks` folder. This is to prevent you from having your changes removed if you update your graphic packs inside Cemu. I hope that makes sense.

THEN, we can do the editing. You'll wanna add some ultrawide resolutions to the rules.txt file. Basically something along the lines of: https://github.com/cemu-project/cemu_graphic_packs/blob/61f9a304b70a645bef2570b5d9a0277a9094cfcd/src/SonicLostWorld/Graphics/rules.txt#L93-L139, although it depends on your game. This is to make the game render at a a higher horizontal resolution since you also want to render more.

the final step is to add a `patch_AspectRatioOrWhateverNameYouWant.asm` to your game. A patch should start with something along the lines of:
```
[SkySpyAdv_AspectRatio_V123]
moduleMatches = 0xfab25e0c
```
You'll wanna change the V[number] and moduleMatches numbers. Both of these you can find in your log. For the first one you wanna find the nearest `TitleVersion: v258` line. That is the version you are making the patch for. The second one you can find by finding the first line that starts with `[00:38:42.075] Loaded module 'YOUR_RPX_NAME_I_THINK' with checksum 0xXXXXXXXXX`.

After this is done you can use the entire syntax that https://wiki.cemu.info/wiki/Cemu_patches details. A lot is possible, but if you just want to change a value in memory, you'll only need to add a `0x0123123 = .float ($width/$height)/($gameWidth/$gameHeight` line (with a changed address). This uses the $width and $height defined by the rules.txt file to calculate the aspect ratio.
I hope that helps

you could hook both VPADRead and KPADRead to support both

```asm
[BetterVR_HookInput_V208]
moduleMatches = 0x6267BFD0

.origin = codecave

; r3 = channel
; r4 = status
; r5 = count
; r6 = error
; ret r3 = 0 for success, 1 for failure
hooked_VPADRead:
; prologue
stwu r1, -0x14(r1)
stw r7, 0x14(r1) ; save r7 to use as a temporary register
mflr r7
stw r7, 0x18(r1)

; save registers and run the original function to allow for combined inputs
stw r6, 0x10(r1)
stw r5, 0x0C(r1)
stw r4, 0x08(r1)
stw r3, 0x04(r1)
bl import.vpad.VPADRead

; check if VPAD_CHANNEL parameter is 0 (in r3 register)
lwz r7, 0x04(r1)
cmpwi r7, 0
bne exitHookInput

; check error pointer for OK status (in r6 register)
lwz r7, 0x10(r1)
lwz r7, 0x00(r7)
cmpwi r7, 0
;beq exitHookInput ; uncomment to only enable XR input when also using gamepad input

; overwrite input with XR input
lwz r7, 0x04(r1)
bl import.coreinit.hook_InjectXRInput
; overwrite status with OK if injection was successful
cmpwi r3, 1
bne exitHookInput
lwz r7, 0x10(r1)
li r3, 0
stw r3, 0x00(r7)
li r3, 1


exitHookInput:
; epilogue
lwz r7, 0x18(r1)
mtlr r7
; preserve original function's return values
; lwz r3, 0x04(r1)
; lwz r4, 0x08(r1)
; lwz r5, 0x0C(r1)
; lwz r6, 0x10(r1)
lwz r7, 0x14(r1)
addi r1, r1, 0x14
blr

0x030D9F48 = bla hooked_VPADRead

```assembly
[group_name]
moduleMatches=0xMODULE_CHECKSUM_FROM_LOG

; Somewhere at the top preferably. This is how we place a label at a far-away address.

YourCodeCave:

stw r31, 0x14(r1) ; save r31 so that its available for any modification. If you need these contents you can use another register number
stw r30, 0x10(r1) ; save r30 too
; ... other save/stack stuff
mflr r31 ; move the link register value (which was set to the address after the bl instruction of the initial jump that got us into the codecave) to r31
stw r31, 0x18(r1) ; store the link register value that was put into r31 into the stack. This is usually 0x04 more then the stack size.

; body of the codecave aka your code

; -- long jump example (if the function requires any arguments (aka r3, r4, f0 etc. registers) and you want to modify/add those, make sure to backup/restore them in the stack above/below)
lis r31, RandomAddressForCodeThatsFarAway@ha ; load upper half of the address of the label into upper half of r31
addi r31, r31, RandomAddressForCodeThatsFarAway@l ; load bottom half of the address of the label into lower half of r31 by adding it
; note: r31 now contains the whole address of the location that the label was set to
mtctr r31 ; move the value from r31 into the counter register
bctrl ; branch to the value from the counter register and also set the link register to the next instruction

; epilogue of the function to restore the registers and values we stored earlier
lwz r31, 0x18(r1) ; load the link register value we stored earlier into r31
mtlr r31 ; move the link register value back to r31 so that it is restored and we can use blr to return to the original calling location
lwz r30, 0x10(r1) ; restore the r31 register
lwz r31, 0x14(r1) ; restore the r31 register
addi r1, r1, 0x14 ; decrease stack again after we no longer need it. Make sure this matches with the amount you increase it above.
blr

What even is power pc assembly 😭😭😭 I’m on a MacBook Air

assembly is cpu instructions
you computer uses x86 cpu's and instructions
phones use arm cpu's and instructions
the wii and wii u use power PC cpu's and instructions

all compiled code gets turned into assembly code/instructions
this includes your pythons, java, c, c++, rust etc.
for simple game modding, its usually easiest to just code in cpu instructions directly

so cemu has a debugger. you can find it in `DEBUG -> ppc debugger`
and it opens all these windows
this is prolly the most important window, shows all the cpu instructions of the game, as well as the memory address of all those cpu instructions (memory adress is the 02XXXXXXX number)

this would be the 2nd most important window, contains all the cpu registers
what cpu registers are is 32bits of data that can be written into and read out of
basically temporary data that can be freely manipulated
when someone says "load data from memory into the cpu" they're moving data into the CPU registers, running some instructions to process that data, and then storing the processed data somewhere else in ram

Cemu also has a window to see the current ram
has the address on the left, and all the data in that address

so basically a .asm gfx pack will create or change `cpu instructions` to load data into `cpu registers`, and then may use those registers to edit data in `ram`
I'll go over some of the more common cpu instructions:

math type instructions:
`add rDESTINATION, rSOURCE1, rSOURCE2`
add the values in source1 and source2 and puts them in the destination register
for example `add r16, r9, r12` will add the numbers currently in register 9 and in register 12, and then put the result into r16, deleting what ever was in r16 before
`sub rDESTINATION, rSOURCE1, rSOURCE2`
Subtracts the value in source2 from source1 and puts them in the destination register
for example `sub r17, r6, r21` will subtract the numbers currently in register 21 from the number in register 6, and then put the result into r17, deleting what ever was in r17 before (r17 = r6 - r21)
`addi rDESTINATION, rSOURCE1, VALUE` (addi is short for add immediate)
add the value in source1 and a immediate value thats in the instruction and puts them in the destination register
for example `addi r8, r3, 216` will add the numbers currently in register 3 and the constant 216, and then put the result into r16, deleting what ever was in r8 before
`subi rDESTINATION, rSOURCE1, VALUE` (addi is short for add immediate)
subtracts a immediate value thats in the instruction from source1 and puts them in the destination register
for example `subi r3, r10, 7` will subtract 7 from the number currently in r10, and then put the result into r3, deleting what ever was in r3 before (r3 = r10 - 7)
there are also instructions:
 `mullw` (multiply) `mulli` (multiply immediate) `divw` (divide) 
they have the same formatting as above
there is also the `li rDESTINATION, VALUE` (load immediate instruction)
and example is `li r20, 4` loads a value of 4 into register 20 deleting what ever was in register 20 before

bit operation instructions:
`or rDESTINATION, rSOURCE1, rSOURCE2`
`ori rDESTINATION, rSOURCE1, VALUE`
`and rDESTINATION, rSOURCE1, rSOURCE2`
`andi rDESTINATION, rSOURCE1, VALUE`
has `xor` `nand` `nor` as well
if this confuses you, look up logic gates

some definitions you'll need to know before proceding
a byte = 8 bits (a bit is one 1/0)
a halfword = 16 bits or 2 bytes
a word = 4 bytes or 32 bits
every cpu instruction is 32 bits and each register can hold a max of 32 bits

memory address can be represented as a number, and all of the wii u's memory addresses can be represented as a 32 bit number

memory storage type instructions:
`lwz rDESTINATION VALUE(rADDRESS)` (load word and zero)
loads into rDESTINATION the 4 bytes that are in the memory address that the number in rADDRESS points too. if VALUE is something thats not 0, add it to the memory address in rADDRESS and read from that memory instead. 
an example is `lwz r7, 0(r31)` reads the memory address that the value in r31 points too, and then puts the 4 bytes after that address into r7
an other example is `lwz r0, 200(r5)`  reads the memory 200 bytes ahead of the address in r5, and stores the 4 bytes into r0
`lwz r0, -400(r5)` you can also subtract
for values less than 4 bytes `lhz` (load half word and zero), `lbz` (load byte and zero) same formatting as above

`stw rSOURCE VALUE(rADDRESS)` (store word)
stores the 4 bytes that are in rSOURCE to the memory address that the number in rADDRESS points too. if VALUE is something thats not 0, add it to the memory address in rADDRESS and store into that memory instead. 
an example is `stw r3, 0(r4)` stores the 4 bytes that are in r3 to the memory address that the value in r4 points too
an other example is `stw r7, 140(r6)`  stores the 4 bytes that are in r7 to the memory address that the value in r6 points too + 140
`stw r7, -4(r6)` you can also subtract
for values less than 4 bytes `sth` (store half word), `stb` (store byte) same formatting as above

`brach` instructions are also very important 
there is a non numbered cpu register called the `link register` or `LR`
some branch instructions are
`b` (branch)

`cmpw rSOURCE1 rSOURCE2` (compare word) (compares 2 registers)
`beq` (branch if equal) (need to call `cmpw` or `cmpwi` before it)


`cmpwi rSOURCE1 VALUE` (compare word immediate) (compares a register and a value)
`bgt` (branch if greater than) (need to call `cmpw` or `cmpwi` before it)

`blt` (branch if less than) (need to call `cmpw` or `cmpwi` before it)

`bge` (branch if greater than or equal) (need to call `cmpw` or `cmpwi` before it)

`ble` (branch if less than or equal) (need to call `cmpw` or `cmpwi` before it)

`bl` (branch link) branches and updates the link register with the address of the last read instruction.
there are also all the conditionals for branch link as well.
